---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Nav from '../../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
import Breadcrumb from '../../components/Breadcrumb.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Getting Started with OpenLeash: Your First AI Agent Authorization — OpenLeash"
  description="A step-by-step tutorial: install OpenLeash, create an owner, register an agent, write a YAML authorization policy, authorize an action, and verify the cryptographic proof token."
  ogImage="/og/blog.png"
  canonicalPath="/blog/getting-started-with-openleash"
  keywords="OpenLeash tutorial, AI agent authorization setup, how to authorize AI agents, OpenLeash getting started, YAML policy tutorial, PASETO proof token tutorial"
  datePublished="2026-04-10"
  dateModified="2026-04-10"
  jsonLd={[{
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'Article',
    headline: 'Getting Started with OpenLeash: Your First AI Agent Authorization',
    description: 'A step-by-step tutorial: install OpenLeash, create an owner, register an agent, write a YAML authorization policy, authorize an action, and verify the proof token.',
    datePublished: '2026-04-10',
    dateModified: '2026-04-10',
    author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'OpenLeash', url: 'https://openleash.ai' },
    publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'OpenLeash', url: 'https://openleash.ai', logo: { '@type': 'ImageObject', url: 'https://openleash.ai/brand/openleash-mark.svg' } },
    mainEntityOfPage: { '@type': 'WebPage', '@id': 'https://openleash.ai/blog/getting-started-with-openleash' },
    image: 'https://openleash.ai/og.png',
  }]}
>
  <Nav />

  <main class="container">
    <header class="page-header fade-in">
      <Breadcrumb items={[
        { label: 'Home', href: '/' },
        { label: 'Blog', href: '/blog' },
        { label: 'Getting Started', href: '/blog/getting-started-with-openleash' },
      ]} />
      <h1 class="page-title">Getting Started with OpenLeash: Your First AI Agent Authorization</h1>
      <p class="page-desc">
        From zero to a verified proof token in under 10 minutes. Install OpenLeash, write a policy, authorize an action, and verify the cryptographic proof.
      </p>
      <div class="page-meta">
        <time datetime="2026-04-10">April 10, 2026</time>
        <span class="meta-sep">·</span>
        <span>8 min read</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <article class="content fade-in fade-in-d1">
      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>What You Will Build</h2>
        <p>
          By the end of this tutorial, you will have a running OpenLeash instance with an owner account,
          a registered agent, a YAML authorization policy, and a verified proof token. The entire setup
          runs locally — no cloud services, no databases, no external dependencies beyond Node.js.
        </p>
        <p>
          Here is the flow: install OpenLeash, run the interactive wizard to create an owner and agent,
          write a policy that controls spending, send an authorization request, and verify the proof token
          that comes back. Each step builds on the previous one.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Prerequisites</h2>
        <p>
          You need <strong>Node.js 20 or later</strong> and <strong>npm</strong>. That is it. OpenLeash
          is a single npm package with no native dependencies. Check your version:
        </p>

        <CodeBlock
          title="Check Node.js version"
          lines={[
            { type: 'cmd', text: 'node --version', prompt: '$' },
            { type: 'output', text: 'v22.4.0' },
          ]}
        />
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Step 1: Install and Initialize</h2>
        <p>
          Install OpenLeash globally or use <code>npx</code> to run it directly. The <code>wizard</code>
          command walks you through initial setup: it creates a data directory, generates signing keys,
          and sets up your first owner account.
        </p>

        <CodeBlock
          title="Install and run the wizard"
          lines={[
            { type: 'cmd', text: 'npx openleash wizard', prompt: '$' },
            { type: 'output', text: '' },
            { type: 'output', text: '  OpenLeash Setup Wizard' },
            { type: 'output', text: '  ======================' },
            { type: 'output', text: '' },
            { type: 'output', text: '  ? Enter a display name for the owner:' },
            { type: 'output', text: '  > Alice' },
            { type: 'output', text: '' },
            { type: 'output', text: '  ? Enter a passphrase (min 8 chars):' },
            { type: 'output', text: '  > ********' },
            { type: 'output', text: '' },
            { type: 'output', text: '  Created owner: usr_01HQ3...' },
            { type: 'output', text: '  Generated Ed25519 signing keypair' },
            { type: 'output', text: '  Created data directory: ./data' },
            { type: 'output', text: '' },
            { type: 'output', text: '  Setup complete. Run `npx openleash start` to begin.' },
          ]}
        />

        <p>
          The wizard creates a <code>./data</code> directory containing your owner file, signing keys,
          and a state index. All state is file-based — you can inspect, version control, or back up
          the data directory at any time.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Step 2: Start the Server</h2>
        <p>
          Start the OpenLeash sidecar. It runs as a local HTTP server on port 8787 by default and includes
          a web GUI for managing agents, policies, and approval requests.
        </p>

        <CodeBlock
          title="Start the server"
          lines={[
            { type: 'cmd', text: 'npx openleash start', prompt: '$' },
            { type: 'output', text: '' },
            { type: 'output', text: '  OpenLeash v0.14.0' },
            { type: 'output', text: '  Listening on http://127.0.0.1:8787' },
            { type: 'output', text: '  GUI available at http://127.0.0.1:8787/gui' },
          ]}
        />

        <p>
          Open <code>http://127.0.0.1:8787/gui</code> in your browser to access the owner portal.
          Log in with the passphrase you set during the wizard. From here you can create agent invites,
          manage policies, and review approval requests.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Step 3: Register an Agent</h2>
        <p>
          Agents register by accepting an invite and providing an Ed25519 public key. The invite flow
          ensures only agents you authorize can connect. You can create an invite through the GUI
          or the API. Here we will use the TypeScript SDK from the agent's perspective:
        </p>

        <CodeBlock
          title="agent-setup.ts — Register with OpenLeash"
          lines={[
            { type: 'code', text: 'import {' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  generateEd25519Keypair,' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  registerAgent,' },
            { type: 'code', text: '} from &quot;@openleash/sdk&quot;;' },
            { type: 'code', text: '' },
            { type: 'comment', text: '// Generate a keypair for the agent' },
            { type: 'code', text: 'const keypair = await generateEd25519Keypair();' },
            { type: 'code', text: '' },
            { type: 'comment', text: '// Register using the invite code from the owner' },
            { type: 'code', text: 'const agent = await registerAgent({' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  baseUrl: &quot;http://127.0.0.1:8787&quot;,' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  inviteCode: &quot;inv_01HQ3...&quot;,  // from GUI or API' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  publicKey: keypair.publicKey,' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  privateKey: keypair.privateKey,' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  name: &quot;Shopping Agent&quot;,' },
            { type: 'code', text: '});' },
            { type: 'code', text: '' },
            { type: 'code', text: 'console.log(&quot;Agent ID:&quot;, agent.agentId);' },
            { type: 'comment', text: '// Agent ID: agt_01HQ3...' },
          ]}
        />

        <p>
          The agent is now registered and bound to the owner. It can send authorization requests,
          but all requests will be denied until you create a policy that allows specific actions.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Step 4: Write a Policy</h2>
        <p>
          Policies define what actions an agent can perform and under what conditions. They are YAML files
          stored in <code>./data/policies/</code>. Here is a policy that allows the agent to make purchases
          under $100, requires human approval for $100-$500, and denies anything above $500:
        </p>

        <CodeBlock
          title="data/policies/spending-policy.yaml"
          lines={[
            { type: 'code', text: 'id: pol_spending_limit' },
            { type: 'code', text: 'name: Spending Limit Policy' },
            { type: 'code', text: 'description: Controls agent purchasing behavior' },
            { type: 'code', text: '' },
            { type: 'code', text: 'rules:' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  - action: &quot;purchase.*&quot;' },
            { type: 'code', text: '    effect: ALLOW' },
            { type: 'code', text: '    conditions:' },
            { type: 'code', text: '      - field: context.amount' },
            { type: 'code', text: '        operator: lt' },
            { type: 'code', text: '        value: 100' },
            { type: 'code', text: '' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  - action: &quot;purchase.*&quot;' },
            { type: 'code', text: '    effect: REQUIRE_APPROVAL' },
            { type: 'code', text: '    conditions:' },
            { type: 'code', text: '      - field: context.amount' },
            { type: 'code', text: '        operator: gte' },
            { type: 'code', text: '        value: 100' },
            { type: 'code', text: '      - field: context.amount' },
            { type: 'code', text: '        operator: lte' },
            { type: 'code', text: '        value: 500' },
            { type: 'code', text: '' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  - action: &quot;purchase.*&quot;' },
            { type: 'code', text: '    effect: DENY' },
            { type: 'code', text: '    conditions:' },
            { type: 'code', text: '      - field: context.amount' },
            { type: 'code', text: '        operator: gt' },
            { type: 'code', text: '        value: 500' },
          ]}
        />

        <p>
          You can also create and manage policies through the CLI (<code>npx openleash policy upsert</code>)
          or the owner API. Policies take effect immediately — no server restart required.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Step 5: Authorize an Action</h2>
        <p>
          Now the agent can request authorization before performing actions. The SDK handles Ed25519
          request signing automatically. Here is an authorization request for a $45 purchase:
        </p>

        <CodeBlock
          title="agent-action.ts — Request authorization"
          lines={[
            { type: 'code', text: 'import { authorize } from &quot;@openleash/sdk&quot;;' },
            { type: 'code', text: '' },
            { type: 'code', text: 'const result = await authorize({' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  baseUrl: &quot;http://127.0.0.1:8787&quot;,' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  privateKey: keypair.privateKey,' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  agentId: &quot;agt_01HQ3...&quot;,' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  action: &quot;purchase.order&quot;,' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  context: {' },
            { type: 'code', text: '    amount: 45,' },
            { type: 'code', text: '    currency: &quot;USD&quot;,' },
            { type: 'code', text: '    vendor: &quot;example-store&quot;,' },
            { type: 'code', text: '    description: &quot;Office supplies&quot;,' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  },' },
            { type: 'code', text: '});' },
            { type: 'code', text: '' },
            { type: 'code', text: 'console.log(result.decision);' },
            { type: 'comment', text: '// "ALLOW"' },
            { type: 'code', text: '' },
            { type: 'code', text: 'console.log(result.proof_token);' },
            { type: 'comment', text: '// "v4.public.eyJ..."' },
          ]}
        />

        <p>
          The request is evaluated against the spending policy. Since $45 is under the $100 threshold,
          the decision is <code>ALLOW</code> and OpenLeash returns a signed PASETO proof token. The agent
          can now proceed with the purchase and present the proof token to the vendor.
        </p>
        <p>
          If the agent had requested a $250 purchase, the decision would be <code>REQUIRE_APPROVAL</code>,
          and the agent would need to wait for the owner to approve through the GUI or API. A $600 purchase
          would be denied outright.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Step 6: Verify the Proof Token</h2>
        <p>
          The counterparty (the service receiving the agent's request) verifies the proof token to confirm
          the action was authorized. Verification can be done offline using the owner's public key or
          online by calling the OpenLeash verification endpoint:
        </p>

        <CodeBlock
          title="verify.ts — Verify proof token (offline)"
          lines={[
            { type: 'code', text: 'import { verifyProofOffline } from &quot;@openleash/sdk&quot;;' },
            { type: 'code', text: '' },
            { type: 'comment', text: '// Public key from GET /v1/public-keys' },
            { type: 'code', text: 'const publicKey = &quot;...owner-ed25519-public-key...&quot;;' },
            { type: 'code', text: '' },
            { type: 'code', text: 'const verified = await verifyProofOffline({' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  token: result.proof_token,' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  publicKey,' },
            { type: 'code', text: '});' },
            { type: 'code', text: '' },
            { type: 'code', text: 'console.log(verified.action);' },
            { type: 'comment', text: '// "purchase.order"' },
            { type: 'code', text: '' },
            { type: 'code', text: 'console.log(verified.decision);' },
            { type: 'comment', text: '// "ALLOW"' },
            { type: 'code', text: '' },
            { type: 'code', text: 'console.log(verified.constraints);' },
            { type: 'comment', text: '// { max_amount: 100, currency: "USD" }' },
          ]}
        />

        <p>
          Offline verification uses only the public key and the token itself — no network call to OpenLeash.
          This means proof tokens work even when the authorization server is offline, across different networks,
          and with zero additional latency.
        </p>
        <p>
          For online verification (useful when you do not have the public key cached), use the
          <code>POST /v1/verify-proof</code> endpoint or <code>verifyProofOnline()</code> in the SDK.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>What Happens in the Audit Log</h2>
        <p>
          Every authorization decision is recorded in the append-only audit log at <code>./data/audit.log.jsonl</code>.
          Each line is a JSON object with the full request, decision, policy matches, and timestamp.
          The log is useful for debugging policy behavior, compliance reporting, and understanding
          how your agent is operating over time.
        </p>

        <CodeBlock
          title="Audit log entry"
          lines={[
            { type: 'code', text: '{' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  "timestamp": "2026-04-10T12:00:00.000Z",' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  "agent_id": "agt_01HQ3...",' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  "action": "purchase.order",' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  "decision": "ALLOW",' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  "matched_policies": ["pol_spending_limit"],' },
            { type: 'code', text: '  "context": { "amount": 45, "currency": "USD" }' },
            { type: 'code', text: '}' },
          ]}
        />
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>Next Steps</h2>
        <p>
          You now have a working authorization setup. From here you can:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Write more policies for different action types (email, file access, API calls)</li>
          <li>Set up approval workflows for high-value actions</li>
          <li>Integrate the SDK into your agent framework (works with LangChain, CrewAI, AutoGen, or any custom agent)</li>
          <li>Deploy OpenLeash as a Docker container for production use</li>
          <li>Use the <a href="/playground">interactive playground</a> to test policy evaluation</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          For more depth, explore the <a href="/concepts/ai-agent-authorization">AI agent authorization concepts</a>,
          learn <a href="/blog/paseto-vs-jwt-for-ai-agents">why we chose PASETO over JWT</a> for proof tokens,
          or read about <a href="/blog/why-ai-agents-need-authorization">why AI agents need authorization</a>
          in production systems. The full API reference and policy language documentation are available in the
          <a href="/docs">documentation</a>.
        </p>
      </section>
    </article>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page-header {
    padding-top: 40px;
    margin-bottom: 40px;
  }

  .page-title {
    font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 5vw, 2.4rem);
    font-weight: 700;
    margin-bottom: 12px;
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  .page-desc {
    max-width: 680px;
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .page-meta {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 8px;
    margin-top: 12px;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
  }

  .meta-sep {
    color: var(--text-muted);
  }

  .content {
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
    margin-bottom: 48px;
  }

  .content-section {
    margin-bottom: 36px;
  }

  .content-section h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin-bottom: 12px;
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  .content-section p {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: 12px;
    max-width: 680px;
  }

  .content-section ul,
  .content-section ol {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: 12px;
    max-width: 680px;
    padding-left: 24px;
  }

  .content-section li {
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }

  .content-section em {
    color: var(--text-primary);
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .content-section a {
    color: var(--green-bright);
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: color 0.2s var(--ease-out);
  }

  .content-section a:hover {
    color: var(--amber-bright);
  }

  .content-section code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.85em;
    color: var(--green-bright);
    background: rgba(52, 211, 153, 0.08);
    padding: 2px 6px;
    border-radius: 4px;
  }

  .content-section strong {
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }
</style>
